ldier in the English Civil War. He was captured in 1643 and died in prison in 1656."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Alexander","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Alexander de Stanhope was born about 1270, in Stanhope, Durham, England, United Kingdom, his father, Robert de Stanhope, was 11268 and his mother, Mrs. Robert De Stanhope, was 21. He married Agnes Lascelles in 1300, in Stanhope, Durham, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. He died about 1360, in his hometown, at the age of 92."},"et":{"about 1270–about 1360":"umbes 1270–umbes 1360","1260–Male":"1260–Surnud","1270–1360":"1270–1360","1286–Female":"1286–Surnud","1300–1376":"1300–1376","1300–1390":"1300–1390","1248–Male":"1248–Surnud","1251–1330":"1251–1330","about 1360":"umbes 1360","about 1270":"umbes 1270","1330":"1330","1286":"1286","1251":"1251","1360":"1360","1260":"1260","1270":"1270","1390":"1390","1248":"1248","1300":"1300","1376":"1376","Abt 1330":"umbes 1330","about 1300":"umbes 1300","Stanhope, Weardale, Durham, England":"Stanhope, Durham, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Durham, England, United Kingdom":"Durham, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Stanhope, Durham, England, United Kingdom":"Stanhope, Durham, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Stanhope Castle, Stanhope, Durham, E